globos.longText: This assay uses purified genomic DNA, solution based circular capture probes, exonuclease cleanup and PCR barcoding/indexing followed by massively parallel sequencing. All mutations detected by Progenity's NextGen Sequencing platform are confirmed using sequencing or alternate methodologies (excluding hemochromatosis).

This interpretation is based on the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this disorder. This analysis does not rule out the presence of disease-causing mutations in other regions of the gene analyzed (e.g. large genomic deletions, promoter mutations) or in other genes, and does not detect germline mosaicism. Rare genetic variants may show results of pseudogene amplification. Although DNA-based testing provides highly accurate results, rare diagnostic findings may occur. Examples such as the following may confound interpretation: rare polymorphisms or genetic variants, blood transfusion, organ or bone marrow transplant, or mislabeled specimens. No test can detect 100% of genetic conditions or carrier status of all individuals. There is a chance that you could be a carrier of or have a genetic condition even if the test results are negative.

Please contact Progenity at 855-293-2639 if you wish to consult with a laboratory director or genetic counselor regarding these results.


A list of references, mutations tested, ethnicity-based detection rates, carrier frequencies and residual risks are all available online at: progenity.com/preparent-globalplus-022016


To receive a paper copy, please call Progenity Client Services at +1 855-293-2639 and request the following mutation list: Global Plus 022016. Original report is on file and available upon request.
Autosomal Recessive

This laboratory-developed test was developed and its performance characteristics validated by Progenity, Inc. under federal CLIA laboratory guidelines. The test has not been cleared or approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. This test is used for clinical purposes. It should not be regarded as investigational or for research only.

Worldwide, phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency affects about 1 in 15,000 births. However, the frequency varies between populations. It is particularly common in individuals from Turkey, Ireland, some other Northern European countries, and East Asia.
HOW COMMON IS PHENYLALANINE HYDROXYLASE DEFICIENCY?

• Phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern.
  • A patient who has only one mutation in this gene is a carrier. Carriers typically have no signs or symptoms of disease.
  • The family history is usually negative.
  • Carriers have an increased chance to have an affected child. If both parents are carriers of mutations in the PAH gene, there is a 1 in 4 (25%) chance for each child to inherit two mutations and be affected with the disease.
INHERITANCE OF PHENYLALANINE HYDROXYLASE DEFICIENCY
These results indicate that this patient has a higher chance to have a child affected with Phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency.

Genetic counseling is an option to discuss the potential clinical and reproductive implications of these results, as well as testing additional at-risk family members.

Evaluate partner carrier status.

  • Offer carrier screening if the partner has not yet been tested. Consider the pros and cons of different test methodologies. Partners of a known carrier may benefit from more comprehensive, sensitive testing.
  • If the partner has had carrier screening for this condition, review the results. If results were negative, evaluate the detection rate of the test for this condition. Some tests or conditions have low detection rates. In some cases, offering additional testing may be appropriate.

If at-risk, offer appropriate preconception or prenatal testing options. If both partners are carriers for this condition, any pregnancy has a 1 in 4 (25%) risk to be affected.
Phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency carrier status

Phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency refers to the group of disorders caused by intolerance to dietary phenylalanine. These include phenylketonuria (PKU), non-PKU hyperphenylalaninemia, and variant PKU. Without avoidance of phenylalanine, children with PKU historically developed progressive severe intellectual disability. Other forms are associated with varying risk.


Phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency is now detected through newborn screening in almost all cases. Phe-free medical formula and a low protein diet from early in life avoids most serious complications. Women with phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency need to maintain a well controlled Phe-restricted diet from several months before conception through pregnancy to avoid fetal exposure to high levels.
WHAT IS PHENYLALANINE HYDROXYLASE DEFICIENCY?
REPRODUCTIVE OPTIONS FOR CARRIERS

Autosomal Recessive

If both partners are carriers of this disorder, there is a 1 in 4 (25%) chance for any pregnancy to be affected. Reproductive options are available for couples that wish to lower or avoid the risk.


If this patient is pregnant, options include:

  • Continuing the pregnancy without any prenatal testing. Testing should be performed after delivery to diagnose or rule out the condition.
  • Prenatal diagnosis with chorionic villus sampling (CVS) or amniocentesis, depending on the gestational age. When the parental mutations are known, prenatal diagnosis is available. Results may be important for parents for preparation purposes, or for reproductive decision-making.

If this patient is not yet pregnant, options include:

  • Becoming pregnant naturally, and considering the options listed above
  • Preimplantation genetic diagnosis (PGD)
  • Gamete donation
  • Adoption

This assay uses purified genomic DNA, solution based circular capture probes, exonuclease cleanup and PCR barcoding/indexing followed by massively parallel sequencing. All mutations detected by Progenity's NextGen Sequencing platform are confirmed using sequencing or alternate methodologies (excluding hemochromatosis).

This interpretation is based on the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this disorder. This analysis does not rule out the presence of disease-causing mutations in other regions of the gene analyzed (e.g. large genomic deletions, promoter mutations) or in other genes, and does not detect germline mosaicism. Rare genetic variants may show results of pseudogene amplification. Although DNA-based testing provides highly accurate results, rare diagnostic findings may occur. Examples such as the following may confound interpretation: rare polymorphisms or genetic variants, blood transfusion, organ or bone marrow transplant, or mislabeled specimens. No test can detect 100% of genetic conditions or carrier status of all individuals. There is a chance that you could be a carrier of or have a genetic condition even if the test results are negative.

Autosomal Recessive

Analysis of the alpha globin gene cluster was performed on purified genomic DNA using multiplex ligation-dependent probe amplification (MLPA), capillary electrophoresis on an ABI Genetic Analyzer, and manual analysis of fragment profiles using Coffalyser.net version 140721.1958. The probe mix used in the assay (P140-C1; MRC Holland, Amsterdam, The Netherlands) targets HBA1, HBA2, several regions up- and downstream of the two alpha globin genes, and 11 reference probes required for normalization. The following seven deletions (-α3.7, -α4.2, --SEA, --FIL, --THAI, --MED, and -α20.5) are analyzed and reported. Probe ratios less than 0.8 were interpreted as copy number losses and ratios greater than 1.2 as copy number gains. Analytic sensitivity and specificity of the assay have been calculated as >99% (95% CI: 99.18% to 100.00%) and >99% (95% CI: 99.53% to 100.00%), respectively.

Multiplex ligation-dependent probe amplification (MLPA) is designed to determine relative copy number at specific target sequences. MLPA will not detect most inversions, balanced translocations, or copy number changes that lie outside (or only partially inside) the sequence detected by an MLPA probe. Furthermore, a deletion may not be detected when a similarly sized duplication is present on the other allele. Only the following seven deletions (-α3.7, -α4.2, --SEA, --FIL, --THAI, --MED, and -α20.5) are analyzed and reported. Other deletions, deleterious point mutations, or small sequence variants will not be detected. It should be noted that there are potential sources of diagnostic error, including somatic heterogeneity of the sample, misidentification of samples prior to receipt, and polymorphisms or other rare genetic variants that interfere with analysis. Due to the limitations of the assay, there is a chance of a false negative result.

This assay uses purified genomic DNA, solution based circular capture probes, exonuclease cleanup and PCR barcoding/indexing followed by massively parallel sequencing. All mutations detected by Progenity's NextGen Sequencing platform are confirmed using sequencing or alternate methodologies (excluding hemochromatosis).

This interpretation is based on the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this disorder. Examples such as the following may confound interpretation: rare polymorphisms or genetic variants, blood transfusion, organ or bone marrow transplant, or mislabeled specimens. No test can detect 100% of genetic conditions or carrier status of all individuals. There is a chance that you could be a carrier of or have a genetic condition even if the test results are negative.

This assay uses purified genomic DNA, solution based circular capture probes, exonuclease cleanup and PCR barcoding/indexing followed by massively parallel sequencing. All mutations detected by Progenity's NextGen Sequencing platform are confirmed using sequencing or alternate methodologies (excluding hemochromatosis).

This interpretation is based on the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this disorder. This analysis does not rule out the presence of disease-causing mutations in other regions of the gene analyzed (e.g. large genomic deletions, promoter mutations) or in other genes, and does not detect germline mosaicism. Rare genetic variants may show results of pseudogene amplification. Although DNA-based testing provides highly accurate results, rare diagnostic findings may occur. Examples such as the following may confound interpretation: rare polymorphisms or genetic variants, blood transfusion, organ or bone marrow transplant, or mislabeled specimens. No test can detect 100% of genetic conditions or carrier status of all individuals. There is a chance that you could be a carrier of or have a genetic condition even if the test results are negative.

This assay uses purified genomic DNA, solution based circular capture probes, exonuclease cleanup and PCR barcoding/indexing followed by massively parallel sequencing. All mutations detected by Progenity's NextGen Sequencing platform are confirmed using sequencing or alternate methodologies (excluding hemochromatosis).

This interpretation is based on the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this disorder. This analysis does not rule out the presence of disease-causing mutations in other regions of the gene analyzed (e.g. large genomic deletions, promoter mutations) or in other genes, and does not detect germline mosaicism. Rare genetic variants may show results of pseudogene amplification. Although DNA-based testing provides highly accurate results, rare diagnostic findings may occur. Examples such as the following may confound interpretation: rare polymorphisms or genetic variants, blood transfusion, organ or bone marrow transplant, or mislabeled specimens. No test can detect 100% of genetic conditions or carrier status of all individuals. There is a chance that you could be a carrier of or have a genetic condition even if the test results are negative.

choices.name: ACADVLDA1
choices.description: Progenity - Very long-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency

globos.longText: This assay uses purified genomic DNA, solution based circular capture probes, exonuclease cleanup and PCR barcoding/indexing followed by massively parallel sequencing. All mutations detected by Progenity's NextGen Sequencing platform are confirmed using sequencing or alternate methodologies (excluding hemochromatosis).

This interpretation is based on the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this disorder. This analysis does not rule out the presence of disease-causing mutations in other regions of the gene analyzed (e.g. large genomic deletions, promoter mutations) or in other genes, and does not detect germline mosaicism. Rare genetic variants may show results of pseudogene amplification. Although DNA-based testing provides highly accurate results, rare diagnostic findings may occur. Examples such as the following may confound interpretation: rare polymorphisms or genetic variants, blood transfusion, organ or bone marrow transplant, or mislabeled specimens. No test can detect 100% of genetic conditions or carrier status of all individuals. There is a chance that you could be a carrier of or have a genetic condition even if the test results are negative.

Please contact Progenity at 855-293-2639 if you wish to consult with a laboratory director or genetic counselor regarding these results.


A list of references, mutations tested, ethnicity-based detection rates, carrier frequencies and residual risks are all available online at: progenity.com/preparent-globalplus-022016


To receive a paper copy, please call Progenity Client Services at +1 855-293-2639 and request the following mutation list: Global Plus 022016. Original report is on file and available upon request.

This assay uses purified genomic DNA, solution based circular capture probes, exonuclease cleanup and PCR barcoding/indexing followed by massively parallel sequencing. All mutations detected by Progenity's NextGen Sequencing platform are confirmed using sequencing or alternate methodologies (excluding hemochromatosis).

This interpretation is based on the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this disorder. This analysis does not rule out the presence of disease-causing mutations in other regions of the gene analyzed (e.g. large genomic deletions, promoter mutations) or in other genes, and does not detect germline mosaicism. Rare genetic variants may show results of pseudogene amplification. Although DNA-based testing provides highly accurate results, rare diagnostic findings may occur. Examples such as the following may confound interpretation: rare polymorphisms or genetic variants, blood transfusion, organ or bone marrow transplant, or mislabeled specimens. No test can detect 100% of genetic conditions or carrier status of all individuals. There is a chance that you could be a carrier of or have a genetic condition even if the test results are negative.

Please contact Progenity at 855-293-2639 if you wish to consult with a laboratory director or genetic counselor regarding these results.

Fragile X: A single-tube CGG repeat primed PCR based assay using two gene-specific primers that flank the triplet repeat along with a third primer that is complementary to the (CGG)n repeat was used to determine genotypes for CGG allele sizes within the Fragile X gene (FMR1). This assay will identify alleles of all sizes but cannot determine methylation status of expanded alleles. In >99% of cases, Fragile X syndrome is caused by an expansion of CGG repeat sequences in the FMR1 gene; non-expansion type mutations are not detected by this assay. This test detects full mutation expansions up to at least 1200 CGG repeats, and accurately sizes products with ≤ 200 CGG repeats. The accuracy of this methodology is +/- 1 for 0-54 CGG repeats, +/- 2 for 55-70 CGG repeats, +/- 3 for 71-120 CGG repeats, and +/- 5 for 121-200 CGG repeats.

Fragile X: In >99% of cases, Fragile X syndrome is caused by an expansion of CGG repeat sequences in the FMR1 gene; non-expansion type mutations are not detected by this assay. This interpretation is based on the clinical information provided and the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this condition. This assay cannot determine the number of FMR1 alleles or the number of X chromosomes. No test can detect 100% of genetic conditions or carrier status of all individuals. LIMITATIONS

In >99% of cases, fragile X syndrome is caused by an expansion of CGG repeat sequences in the FMR1 gene; non-expansion type mutations are not detected by this assay. This interpretation is based on the clinical information provided and the current understanding of the molecular genetics of this condition. Although DNA-based testing provides highly accurate results, rare diagnostic errors may occur. Examples include misinterpretation because of polymorphisms or rare genetic variants, blood transfusion, mislabeled specimens. Bone marrow transplants from allogenic donors will interfere with testing. This test detects full mutation expansions up to at least 1200 CGG repeats, and accurately sizes products with ≤ 200 CGG repeats.  The accuracy of this methodology is +/- 1 for 0-54 CGG repeats, +/- 2 for 55-70 CGG repeats, +/- 3 for 71-120 CGG repeats, and +/- 5 for 121-200 CGG repeats.  

 

ADDITIONAL INFORMATION

For references, please visit: progenity.com/references. Original report is on file and available upon request.
